  "review": "This paper introduces Graph Edit Networks (GENs), a novel output layer for Graph Neural Networks designed to predict graph edits, encompassing node and edge changes. The core idea of mapping node embeddings to discrete graph operations is interesting and addresses a relevant gap in graph-to-graph learning, particularly for time series prediction. The theoretical connection established between graph mappings and teaching signals for GENs (Theorem 2) is a notable contribution, offering a structured approach to training. The empirical evaluation demonstrates strong performance on several synthetic graph dynamical systems, achieving perfect accuracy in some cases, and promising efficiency gains with edge filtering on large graphs.\n\nHowever, the manuscript exhibits several methodological and presentation inconsistencies. The claim of \"linear instead of quadratic\" time complexity is repeatedly made but heavily qualified by the need for \"edge filtering\" and is explicitly contradicted by Algorithm 1's stated O(N^2) complexity for dense graphs. The definition of a graph mapping (Definition 1) is overly complex. The multi-step inference procedure for complex dynamics is a greedy heuristic lacking theoretical guarantees. Crucially, the approach relies on pre-computed or externally provided optimal graph mappings for training, which is an NP-hard problem itself, limiting its end-to-end applicability. Furthermore, the performance on real-world Python syntax tree datasets, relegated to an appendix, shows GENs failing to outperform a simple constant baseline, which significantly undermines the practical utility demonstrated by the synthetic experiments. Fixed thresholds in Algorithm 1 also raise concerns about robustness.",
